gland","Tickhill, Doncaster, South Yorkshire, England":"Tickhill, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Tickhill, Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Tickhill, Yorkshire, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Clarell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Clavel  .","Altered form of French   Clavel  .","Catalan: from <i>clavell</i> ‘clove’, earlier also ‘nail’, applied as a metonymic occupational name for a spice trader or a nail maker."],"variants":[{"name":"Clavel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Alfredo, Angel, Bernardina, Carlos, Consuelo, Fernando, Gustavo, Jeronimo, Jorge, Luis, Margarita.  French Andre, Eugenie, Fernande, Jean-Claude, Pierre.","Spanish: from <i>clavel</i> ‘clove’, earlier also ‘nail’, applied as a metonymic occupational name for a spice trader or a nail maker.","French: from Old French <i>clavel</i> ‘bolt (of a door or gate)’ or ‘nail, link, ring (of chain mail)’, used as a metonymic occupational name for a maker or seller. Compare   Clewell  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":4,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":39,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Clarell III was born about 1220, in Tickhill, Yorkshire, England, his father, John de Clarell, was 18 and his mother, Alianor de Clarell, was 17. He married Johanna in 1251, in Tickhill, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1285, in Doncaster, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 66, and was buried in Tickhill, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"about 1220–1285":"umbes 1220–1285","1220–1285":"1220–1285","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1231–1339":"1231–1339","1232–1292":"1232–1292","1255–1332":"1255–1332","1266–1292":"1266–1292","1203–1285":"1203–1285","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1231":"1231","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","1251":"1251","1292":"1292","12